A constructor is a special memeber function of a class that is automatically called when an object is created. It initializes the data member of the class and prepare the object for use.

Purpose of constructor:
1. for object initialization
2. code reusability
3. Ensures default values

Types of constructor:
1. Non parametrized constructor
2. Parametrized constructor
3. Copy constructor--we can create a copy constructor manually by defining a constructor that takes an object of the same class as a parameter and copies its attributes.

import java.util.*;

class Employee {
    public String employeeName; // To store the name of the employee
    public int salary;          // To store the salary of the employee

    // Parameterized constructor
    public Employee(String name, int salary) {
        this.employeeName = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }
    
    // Copy Constructor
    public Employee(Employee employee) {
        // Calling another constructor
        this(employee.employeeName, employee.salary);
    }
}

// Main Class
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        /* Creating an object of Employee class and passing 
        values for the parameterized constructor */
        Employee obj = new Employee("Raj", 10000);
        
        // Creating a copy of obj using Copy constructor
        Employee objCopy = new Employee(obj);
        
        // Printing the attibutes of copied object
        System.out.println("Name of the copied employee: " + objCopy.employeeName);
        System.out.println("Salary of the copied employee: " + objCopy.salary);
    }
}

